[FULL TEXT ANALYSIS BELOW]
nature aging
https://doi.org/10.1038/s43587-025-00881-7
News & views
Alzheimer’s disease
GLP-1R agonists protect against Alzheimer’s 
disease by rewiring energy regulation
Daxiang Na & Marc Schneeberger Pané
A study from Zhang, Chen, Feng and colleagues 
investigates the multifaceted role of GLP-1R 
agonists in different brain cell types. They show 
that GLP-1R agonists can reduce amyloidosis 
and mitigate Alzheimer’s disease symptoms in 
mice by activating AMPK signaling, regulating 
neuronal amyloid-β metabolism and 
promoting microglial phagocytosis.
Alzheimer’s disease (AD) remains one of the most urgent challenges 
in aging and public health. Over 55 million people worldwide live with 
dementia, and AD accounts for the majority of cases. In the USA alone, 
care for individuals with dementia cost an estimated US $355 billion 
in 2021 (ref. 1), excluding the immense burden of unpaid caregiving 
that is provided by families. More than a century after Alzheimer first 
described the disease, truly effective therapies remain elusive. Despite 
its well-defined pathological hallmarks — such as the accumulation of 
misfolded proteins and chronic neuroinflammation — the origins of 
AD remain complex. Intriguingly, mounting evidence has revealed a 
notable overlap between neurodegenerative and metabolic disorders, 
particularly type 2 diabetes mellitus2. Both diseases share common 
pathophysiological features, including impaired glucose metabolism, 
insulin resistance, chronic inflammation and disrupted cellular energy 
homeostasis. Metabolic dysfunction in diabetes can exacerbate neu-
ronal damage and cognitive decline, and neurodegeneration itself 
can further aggravate metabolic imbalances, which creates a vicious 
cycle. This convergence has opened the door to a new line of thinking: a 
metabolic hormone could reshape AD pathology from within the brain 
itself. GLP-1 receptor agonists (GLP-1RAs) are a class of medications that 
are already revolutionizing the treatment of type 2 diabetes mellitus 
and obesity. The effectiveness and safety of GLP-1RAs in treating or 
preventing obesity have been shown in numerous clinical trials; they 
have multifaceted functions in promoting pancreatic insulin secretion, 
inhibiting glucagon release, promoting satiety, and slowing gastric 
emptying3. In addition to their versatile ability in regulating energy 
metabolism, studies also suggest that GLP-1RAs could help to treat 
neurodegenerative diseases such as AD and Parkinson’s disease4. In 
a recent study in Nature Aging, Zhang, Chen, Feng and colleagues5 
explored the neuroprotective potential of GLP-1RAs, and uncovered 
how these agents might alleviate AD-related pathology. Their findings 
point to AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK) signaling as a key media-
tor, which offers a compelling mechanistic link between metabolic 
regulation and brain health.
The authors began by observing a negative correlation between 
GLP-1 plasma levels and markers of brain energy metabolism and neu-
ropathology in patients with AD and in the APP23/PS45 humanized AD 
mouse model. To explore this relationship, they turned to primary 
neurons isolated from APP23/PS45 mice, and demonstrated that treat-
ment with exendin-4 (a clinically approved GLP-1RA) restored cellular 
energy metabolism in an AMPK-dependent manner. Inhibition of AMPK 
with compound C reversed these effects, which confirms its essential 
role in mediating GLP-1RA action. Furthermore, Zhang, Chen, Feng and 
colleagues demonstrated that GLP-1RAs activate AMPK signaling in 
neurons via a CaMKK-dependent mechanism. Inhibition of CaMKK with 
STO609 diminished AMPK activation in response to GLP-1RAs, which 
highlights CaMKK as an upstream regulator of this metabolic pathway5.
Given previous reports that GLP-1RAs can modulate amyloid-β 
processing, the authors subsequently investigated whether this effect 
also depends on AMPK. Using both primary neurons from APP23/PS45 
mice and the 20E2 human cell line (which stably expresses mutant 
APP), the authors demonstrated that GLP-1RAs reduced the expression 
of the β-secretase BACE1 and its cleavage product, APP C99, without 
altering total APP levels5. These findings suggest a mechanism in which 
GLP-1RAs target amyloid-β metabolism rather than its expression.
To uncover how AMPK suppresses BACE1, the authors focused on 
the transcription factor NF-κB p65, a well-known regulator of BACE1 
expression6. In reporter assays using an exogenous BACE1 promoter 
in N2a mouse neuroblastoma cells, inhibition of AMPK significantly 
