increased BACE1 expression. By contrast, activation of AMPK with AICAR 
suppressed BACE1 expression. These regulatory effects were reflected 
at both the mRNA and protein levels in primary neurons. Notably, AMPK 
inhibition raised nuclear p65 levels and enhanced p65 binding to the 
BACE1 promoter, which provides mechanistic evidence that GLP-1RAs 
reduce amyloidogenic processing through an AMPK–NF-κB axis6.
Zhang, Chen, Feng and colleagues also turned to microglia, which 
are central players in the neuroinflammatory landscape of AD7–9. Using 
RNA sequencing of mouse BV2 microglial cells treated with GLP-1RAs 
and amyloid-β oligomers, the authors found that GLP-1RAs upregulated 
phagocytic genes while downregulating proinflammatory transcripts5. 
These transcriptomic shifts were accompanied by increased microglial 
phagocytic activity and reduced inflammation — effects that were once 
again hindered by AMPK inhibition5. Together, these findings reinforce 
the emerging perspective that GLP-1RAs recalibrate microglial function 
towards a homeostatic, neuroprotective state10.
Although previous epidemiological studies have hinted at a 
reduced incidence of AD among patients treated with GLP-1RAs11, in vivo 
evidence has been limited. Zhang, Chen, Feng and colleagues addressed 
this gap using the APP23/PS45 mouse model. Chronic treatment with 
exendin-4 over 8 weeks (starting at 6 weeks of age) resulted in robust 
AMPK activation, BACE1 suppression and reduced amyloid-β deposi-
tion in brain regions that are critical for cognition, such as the neocor-
tex and hippocampus. Notably, these molecular changes translated 
into reduced inflammation, enhanced microglial phagocytosis and 
improved behavioral performance in a Morris water maze task, which 
collectively reinforce the therapeutic potential of GLP-1RAs5. Crucially, 
these benefits were abolished when AMPK was inhibited, which con-
firms the pathway’s central role in mediating therapeutic effects.
This study presents a compelling multicellular framework in which 
GLP-1RAs confer neuroprotection through AMPK-dependent modula-
tion of both neuronal and microglial function (Fig. 1). The findings are 
particularly impactful given the clinical availability of GLP-1RAs, which 
accelerates the potential for translational application. Moreover, the 
mechanistic link between metabolic regulation and AD pathology opens 
the door for new biomarkers based on metabolic signaling, which could 
complement established diagnostic markers such as amyloid-β and tau.
Beyond their therapeutic promise, these findings also raise several 
exciting questions, including whether GLP-1RAs can influence tau 

